    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Ending Child Poverty</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Janice Zazinski letter questions David Blankenhorn's insinuation (August 16 Op-Ed) that child poverty is result of mother-headed homes (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>David Blankenhorn, president of the Institute for American Values (letter, Aug. 16), insinuates that child poverty is a product of mother-headed homes and that only an end to ''family fragmentation,'' whatever that is, will bring back the American values his institute touts.</p>
        <p>Would he suggest that married couples with children be forbidden to divorce or that single women be banned from having children?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>David Blankenhorn, president of the Institute for American Values (letter, Aug. 16), insinuates that child poverty is a product of mother-headed homes and that only an end to ''family fragmentation,'' whatever that is, will bring back the American values his institute touts.</p>
        <p>Would he suggest that married couples with children be forbidden to divorce or that single women be banned from having children?</p>
        <p>How about these American values, in the tradition of helping those less fortunate get on their feet and become contributing members of society with a real future: quality job training and low-cost day care for mothers and expanded educational opportunities for children?</p>
        <p>JANICE ZAZINSKI  Cambridge, Mass., Aug. 16, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
